[1] Sri Lanka
Date: Tue, 1 Oct 2002 15:11:55 +0100
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Reuters Foundation [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/523506>

Sri Lanka cholera outbreak under control
----------------------------------------
A cholera outbreak in northern Sri Lanka that has claimed 3 lives is
spreading southward, but officials said on Mon 30 Sep 2002 that the
epidemic was under control.
The war-battered Jaffna peninsula confirmed about 30 cases of the
waterborne disease, and health officials said there was at least 1
diagnosis as far south as the central hill city of Kandy. "There has been a
mass influx of people into Jaffna as tourists, so that might account for 1
or 2 people outside the peninsula being identified with the disease,"
health minister Petikirige Dayaratne told Reuters.
Jaffna was cut off from the rest of Sri Lanka throughout much of nearly 2
decades of ethnic conflict, which pitted separatist Tamil Tigers based in
the north and east against the Sinhalese-majority south. But since the
government and rebels began taking steps toward peace with a truce
agreement signed in February 2001, there has been a steady flow of visitors
from the south to Jaffna, and refugees are beginning to return.
"There's a lot more movement of people around, and people returning from
outside the district," said Kandiah Sanmuganathan, the top local official
in the region, adding that the increased movement was likely to blame for
the spread of the disease. But both officials said the cholera was unlikely
to spread further, adding that the Health Department had begun a public
awareness campaign on safe handling of food and water.
"It's important we contain this because the rainy season will start any
day, and there could be flooding which would make it hard to contain,"
Sanmuganathan said.
