[4]Uganda [Cholera and Dysentery]
Date: Wed 18 Sep 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org
Source: Ugandan Weekly Epidemiology Report (Week ending 15 Sep 2002) [edited]

This is the summary of the epidemiological situation in the country as
reported by 52 of the 56 districts. Kaberamaido, Ntungamo, Sembabule, and
Yumbe districts reported highest with all health units reporting, while the
lowest number of health units reporting within districts was recorded in
Lira and Gulu (15 per cent), and Pader had 9 per cent health unit
reporting. There were no reports from Luwero, Bundibugyo, Soroti, and
Moroto districts.
The cholera outbreak has continued in Hoima, but the number of cases is
smaller than in the previous week, with a total of 17 cases reported.
Masindi and Ntungamo reported 4 and 1 cases, respectively, with 1 death in
Masindi.
Dysentery cases were reported in all reporting districts except Rukungiri
and Hoima, the biggest numbers still coming from the northern region. The
leading 12 districts reporting dysentery were: Arua (90), Moyo (66), Mukono
(60), Kisoro (59), Nebbi (48), Adjuman (47),Gulu (45), Mbale (41), Tororo
(41), Katakwi (36), Kasese (36), Kumi (36) . The District Health Teams are
urged to work with the district political leaders in the improvement of
sanitation practices.
